:::summary
Plato (c. 428–348 BC) was an Athenian philosopher and student of Socrates who founded the Academy — the first institution of higher learning in the Western world. His dialogues explore nearly every branch of philosophy and established metaphysical and political ideas that have shaped Western thought for two and a half millennia. Alfred North Whitehead famously described the history of philosophy as "a series of footnotes to Plato."
:::

